.TH SHOREWALL-NFT-RULES 5 "2026-04-20" "shorewall-nft 1.10.0" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
shorewall\-nft\-rules \- firewall rules for shorewall-nft
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.I rules
file is the primary place where you allow or deny specific traffic between
zones.  Rules are checked before the default policy defined in
.IR shorewall\-nft\-policy (5).

The compiler reads this file during the IR-construction pass and emits one
or more nft rules per row into the appropriate zone-pair chain.

The
.I rules
file supports
.B ?SECTION
blocks:
.B ?SECTION NEW
(default),
.BR "?SECTION ESTABLISHED" ,
.BR "?SECTION RELATED" ,
.BR "?SECTION INVALID" ,
.BR "?SECTION UNTRACKED" .
Most operators keep all rules in the
.B NEW
section.

.SH FILE FORMAT
Location:
.I /etc/shorewall/rules
(or inside a merged
.IR /etc/shorewall46/ ).
.PP
Columns are whitespace-separated.  Lines beginning with
.B #
are comments.  Long lines may be continued with a trailing backslash.

.TS
l l l.
Column	Required	Description
_
ACTION	yes	What to do (ACCEPT, DROP, REJECT, DNAT, …)
SOURCE	yes	Source zone or address
DEST	yes	Destination zone or address
PROTO	no	Protocol number or name (tcp, udp, icmp, …)
DPORT	no	Destination port(s) or range
SPORT	no	Source port(s) or range
ORIG_DEST	no	Original destination for DNAT rules
RATE	no	Rate limit (N/unit:burst)
USER	no	User/group match
MARK	no	Connection mark
CONNLIMIT	no	Max concurrent connections from src
TIME	no	Time range match
HEADERS	no	IPv6 header match
SWITCH	no	Runtime switch name
HELPER	no	conntrack helper name
.TE

.SS ACTION syntax
.TP
.B ACCEPT
Pass the packet.
.TP
.B DROP
Silently discard.
.TP
.B REJECT
Discard and notify sender.
.TP
.B DNAT[\fI:addr\fR][\fI:port\fR]
Destination NAT.  Translates the destination to
.IR addr : port .
.TP
.B SNAT[\fI:addr\fR]
Source NAT.
.TP
.B LOG[\fI:level\fR][\fI:prefix\fR]
Log and continue.
.TP
.BI Macro / name
Built-in macro (e.g.
.BR SSH ,
.BR HTTP ,
.BR HTTPS )
or action file.

.SS SOURCE / DEST syntax
.TP
.I zone
Zone name (matches all hosts in that zone).
.TP
.IB zone : address
Zone restricted to a specific address or CIDR prefix.
.TP
.IB zone : dns: hostname
Zone with a DNS-driven nft set for
.I hostname
(populated by shorewalld).
.TP
.IB zone : dnsr: hostname
Like
.B dns:
but uses the active pull resolver backend in shorewalld.
.TP
.IB zone : nfset: name
Reference a named set declared in
.IR shorewall\-nft\-nfsets (5).
.TP
.IB zone :! nfset: name
Negated nfset reference — match packets whose address is
.I not
in the set.
.TP
.B $FW
Shorthand for the firewall zone.
.TP
.B all
Match any zone.
.TP
.B !
address Negated address.

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Basic service access rules:
.RS
.nf
#ACTION  SOURCE  DEST    PROTO   DPORT
ACCEPT   loc     fw      tcp     22
ACCEPT   loc     net     tcp     80,443
ACCEPT   fw      net     tcp     80,443,587
.fi
.RE
.PP
DNAT for inbound web traffic to a DMZ host:
.RS
.nf
DNAT     net     dmz:198.51.100.10   tcp  80
DNAT     net     dmz:198.51.100.10   tcp  443
.fi
.RE
.PP
DNS-driven rule — allow outbound to github.com only:
.RS
.nf
ACCEPT   loc     net:dns:github.com  tcp  443
.fi
.RE
.PP
Rate-limited SSH to prevent brute-force:
.RS
.nf
ACCEPT   net     fw      tcp     22      -   -  3/min:5
.fi
.RE
.PP
Named nfset reference for a CDN allowlist:
.RS
.nf
ACCEPT   net:nfset:allowlist  loc
.fi
.RE

.SH SEE ALSO
